segments.text: Most important question of all, what feelings do you hold in your heart for A&M today?
I was expecting that one, of course, eventually because of the discussion Saturday, but there's just no feeling like it.
I'll always be grateful that I went there and thankful that I went there.
Grateful for the education, not in an academic sense,
But the growth that I had that started there was nurtured in the military and then matured when I came back.
The things that Anna has given me that I could never, ever have expected to have happen, the presidency of the association, the buster speak here once, poor job, but nonetheless did it.
and then a graduation speaker.
Ed Cooper, I always felt, one of the reasons I felt so close to Jack is that he instigated my selection as a graduation speaker.
He insisted it was never him, but it was Ed Cooper, so I mean, I'll accept Ed Cooper, he's a good guy too.
But between them, that was a,
One of the, just, well, just something don't, few people have an opportunity to do.
You know, something I never would have expected.
You can't, you can't, there's just a debt there that you can never pay.
Alright, what have I failed to ask about, to prompt?
Well, in those years, I can't think of, I don't know.
No student years.
What else can we put in here about the student years?
Obviously friends that you made, many of them stayed friends.
We still see each other at reunions and don't see enough.
That's life.
That's the way it is.
I think any problems that were there were probably self-created.
I don't think that I can blame anything that happened on anybody but myself if there were any, whatever negatives were there.
And hopefully they've all, anything that was bad that's been whitewashed by now.
And it's just a tremendous, I don't know what else to tell you.
Now, and there were no incidents, no tragedies that I can think of, any events, any fires, any?
There was a couple of events back when I was a student that I had forgotten about.
One time, we marched on the President's home.
It was in the old President's home, across from the fountain.
And we were objecting to something, probably the erosion of senior privileges.
And I wasn't a senior then, so I don't really remember what it was.
I think it had to do with his
decision that all hazing etc would stop on a certain date?
Well yeah and they took a lot of so-called senior privileges away and we didn't they didn't like that so of course we all marched over there and did riot.
I mentioned this Saturday to Carkey and she said well you were among the first sit-ins and didn't know it and I guess we were and then we also went down to the
then the administration building where the president had his office, and now the Jack K. Williams building, I'm proud to say.
And we slept there one night, as I mentioned to you.
We were objecting to probably again, oh, I think the first time was the fact that we were going to put freshmen at Bryan Field.
It might have been it.
I don't remember.
Sure.
What was the president's reaction to your report?
Well, he came out and said something to us, and we went back to the dorm.
I don't know.
It might have been, too, that Colonel Malloy came out and said, get your panties back to the gun, too.
I don't remember that either.
Then when we went to the administration building, we actually spent the whole night there.
And I slept on one of those steps going up to the president's office.
I slept very well.
And we made class the next morning, for sure.
There was a newspaper article on that in the Houston section of the Chronicle or anyway, Houston Press is where it was.
My picture was in there with some kind of quote, which I also sent to the court center for their archives.
I don't remember what it said anymore.
Do you think of any other topics that we want to include about your student days?
No, but I'd like to think I'd do it all over again if I had to give any opportunity.
There are very little things I would change.
Obviously, I always think of something, but I know I could think of things I would change, but not an awful lot.
It was just a wonderful year and wonderful experience.
That's great.
